segments.text: José María Garza.
Yes.
And where was he born?
He didn't return to Vieja García.
In what year?
And when did he live in Ateas?
And for what reason?
For the revolution.
Ah, yes.
And tell me more about the revolution in these days, please.
Well, before that date when we came here, when we lived in Vieja García,
My father was in charge there.
And when the revolutionaries came in, they came with the...
He was in charge there.
And to give them reason where there was corn, food, whatever.
And they went and looted everything.
And at that time, at about two or three o'clock, those revolutionaries came out and the federals came in.
They were from the government.
After a while, they were thrown out of the billiards and the billiardsmen came in.
After a while, a bandit from Tolentino came in with people.
And that's when the federalists came in again, the trebadores from La Huerta.
There was a day when the money changed every two hours.
It was so cheap, it was worth a kind of money.
It was in paper, billiards that they named it.
Some bills in pesos, in cincos.
In half an hour it was worth a coin, in half an hour another, and it was like that.
And there were dead people hanging there.
They were carried in carts.
They were dodged like dodging firewood.
And there, on the riverbank, they made a well for them, they called it the caracol.
There they just lit the yunta and emptied them to the dead.
There they were carried.
And that's when he took...
Francisco could not get out via Nicamole and Nacataz.
There is a stream of the Cerro del Fraile that goes all the way here, all the way to Mediación, via Gacía, via Gacía's plains.
And they used it as a fence, the billets.
And from there, from Sierra Madre, another came.
It was just a river, a stream, and they couldn't get out of sight.
General Alfonso Vázquez came and started to bring people in.
As he was in charge, they were gathering.
They were from the government who were coming that day.
They were there for three days, and when they had parking spaces in black boxes, that was the park, they would come in and accommodate him there.
At three in the morning, they gave orders to throw Francisco Villa there.
If he turned back, they would thrash him.
It was a push for a decision.
And they came in at about eight in the morning, and people started to come out.
By ten, they started to get injured.
They brought them home and brought them to Monterrey.
At two in the afternoon, General Alfonso Vázquez was killed.
He was shot three times.
He didn't want to be brought back from combat.
He wanted three captains.
When he arrived in Monterrey, he died.
But the people of General Alfonso Vázquez never came back until Francisco Villa was thrown out.
In the port of...
Why did you explain?
He clarified, part of your question was, he clarified that there were different groups.
My father had a lot of corn and everything.
There was whatever they wanted.
If you turned to the other side, they would kill you.
You had to be with them if they wanted to be with us.
Don't go against them.
Don't oppose them.
Because there were too many groups.
Who were they going to favor?
And so they really were neutral.
Right.
But they were the ones that were getting screwed, you know?
Right, right.
The machine guns.
What kind of work did your father have before the revolution?
He was a carpenter.
He made bagpipes.
Morales.
Riatas del azar.
carpets, and a lot of other things that are from Istria.
What did you do with them?
From Istria.
What was that?
Mamey.
From Lechuvía.
From Lechuvía.
And he was the owner there?
He was the owner.
And what did those lands do?
They left them there.
They left them there.
We also have lands there.
If we don't pay taxes, we have nothing.
And they came to Laredo, Texas.
to work in the bakery.
Our older brothers were bakers.
Your older brothers?
How did they learn that trade in Spanish?
The trade.
The trade.
In the bakeries, dad would put them to work, to teach them.
Aunque les pagaran poquito, pero que aprendieran.
He's a baker by trade also.
He's a jack of all trades.
Ah, y así aprendió usted de panadero también.
Y trabajamos en... Ahí en Laredo trabajaron de panaderos.
In 1915 we started working in the panadería El Gallo, in Larero.
In Larero.
In Larero.
There we worked.
His name was Raúl Ornelas, the owner of the bakery.
And one of his sons was Luque Ornelas.
We worked there.
And at 17 we came here to Camargo.
And from Camargo we moved here to Rio Grande.
To work in the bakery.
And my brothers were teachers.
He's got a brother that lives in Monterrey, Mexico.
And you came here to the United States, from Camargo.
Yes, from Camargo.
They brought us here.
After the Revolution.
After the Revolution.
Why did you come to Texas?
Because from here we went to look for Leopoldo Reynaga, who was a baker.
But you had a lot of knowledge here in Rio Grande, right?
Yes, because of the question of being bakers.
And they brought us here so that we could work there.
And why did you stay here in Texas?
Why did your brother Felipe return to Mexico?
But he never lived in Texas.

I was working here in Texas, but because he was a mechanic, any motor that he heard working, he worked in Peñoles, in a factory where he was in charge of just following the engine that was failing, he would tell them to drive it.
But he came back, he preferred to go to Mexico to stay here.
Yes, he did.
Y nosotros, pues, aquí estábamos sacando bien la vida hasta la fecha.
Ya no nos movimos.
Trabajé el 25.
En 1924, trabajamos en San Antonio, en la panadería de Jacobo Estrada.
Era una de las mejores panaderías que había.
Y ahí trabajé en Houston.
Bueno, usted nació en Villa García, ¿no?
En Villa García.
When was it that the U.S. took, they made the Rio Grande border, you know, the American border?
That was in 1845.
That was way after the revolution.
So that means that these people, when they crossed that border, they were actually crossing into a foreign country.
They were crossing into a foreign country.
So, ¿cómo se quedaban aquí legalmente?
Why would the U.S. government let them do that?
I don't know.
How did they cross the border without the American government telling them?
We crossed in Laredo and they just pointed us out.
That's the date.
They were just right on us.
They were just right on us.
That's the date.
And then when we came here, we came here, they charged us with passports.
And when they arrived, they charged us with passports.
We went through the bridge with permission.
They took our passports.
And then when the $8 passports arrived, we took them out.
Everyone took out their passports.
The first time they crossed?
You, when you crossed?
There wasn't.
There wasn't?
There wasn't a passport.
You crossed in 1903?
Yes.
And there wasn't a passport?
There wasn't immigration?
Yes, the reason why we were registered.
Ah, they would just record.
Ah, they just wrote the names of the people.
They didn't write anything.
And they were registered there.
Did it stay there?
There was no limit to how long they could stay here.
There was no limit.
The years went by.
When did the American government require the registration?
Around 1918.
So what did they do?
When the American government demanded that...
The passports were $10.
They could have stayed here in the United States for as long as they wanted.
Right, that's what...
In fact, there weren't even closed checks a lot of places.
A lot of places you just walked across and nobody even asked you to sign your name.
Like I say, the people that lived here, the people that lived there were the same people.
Right, right.
And the border was absolutely big.
In fact, it was up in the 20s that the first real...
close checks began to be made, and it wasn't until about 1930 or in the early 30s that there was any officially enforced close-ups.
That's when she found out that she was an American citizen, when they started enforcing it.
In the 1930s.
Right.
She was going to go get her official citizenship, and she said, you're already a citizen.
What year were you married?
The first time.
A woman from here or from Mexico?
From here.
From the United States?
From the United States.
What was her name?
Maria Aguirre.
And she was from Texas?
She was from Texas.
She was from Texas?
Yes.
And here in Rio Grande.
How did her family come here to Rio Grande?
We lived here.
We lived here.
I don't know.
They probably emigrated in the same conditions.
My husband lived over there in Rivera.
He lived over there in Rivera.
It was Rivera.
Well, sir, tell me a little more about life here in the United States.
Could it be that you were kidnapped again?
What?
Well, tell me a little more about your life here in the United States.
Well, here in the United States I've had a good time.
I've always worked.
Yes.
And we, as we had a bakery office, they came to take us from various places.
Once, they took me to El Cauce, to San Juan, to Quinisville, to...
San Antonio also took me to Dílete, or Mílete, how is San Antonio?
Dílete, yes, or Mílete, it's over there.
Two little places, there's Cotula too.
There have always been better jobs than on the other side.
We knew how to work in the bakery, and we still had the fame of bakers, because we were bakers, and we still are.
¿Y de ahí se divorció usted y de ahí se volvió a casar?
Sí.
My wife is his daughter from the second wife.
¿Y cuánto se casaba la segunda vez?
Cuarenta y cinco.
¿Cuarenta y cinco?
Sí.
¿Y en qué pueblo?
Aquí en Río Grande.
¿En Río Grande?
En Río Grande.
¿Para cuántos años vivía usted en Río Grande?
That's 73 and 63.
In 56 years.
But he was talking about living all these other different places.
He's very old.
Wow.
He wasn't gone for long, you know, just two or three months.
This is from a temple rock.
A temple rock in the pot.
Ah, yes, I understand.
You understand?
Yes.
It took me a month to work.
To work.
Yes, to work.
And all the time, the work class is in the bakery?
In the bakery and...
In the court.
Carpentry and...
In the court.
In the what?
In the court.
Court?
What does the court give you?
Work.
Work in the county.
The same, carpentry, cleaning, and...
Several jobs, a little bit.
I know a little bit of everything.
I'm also a plumber.
Because I've liked learning a little bit of everything.
Yes.
But my profession is a baker.
A baker, yes.
Because I worked in Hebron.
In 1932, I worked in the bakery.
Were you married to my uncle?
No.
He didn't get married until 1945.
And for what reason did you never come back to Mexico?
Well, I had a good time here.
My parents were close by in Camargo.
So...
Working here is good.
But I liked it better here.
So you come here and live well.
My husband died at the age of 79.
He didn't go to jail.
That's what I, you know, I work in the hospital.
We're very interested in health and longevity.
And I'd like to explain to my son how that has been to live so many years.
His whole family has lived extremely well.
And we have both sides of our families.
And I can't understand how come we don't make it.
You know, natural selection.
the infant mortality was probably very high.
Although it varied with families even then.
And you, in the families that you had, since you all had big families, what was the percentage of children that died in childhood?
Of our families?
Well, we were 17 families.
The family that I was in was 17.
It's just like, I used to live in El Paso and the tribe, the Indian tribe, the natives that live there are the Tarahumara.
And I've read some articles that have been written on them.
Sanitation is very poor.
The infant mortality is extremely high, but the people that survive, they all live to be 100 years old.
So that's why I say it's natural selection, survival of the fittest.

Well, there's always been a fallacy about the increasing lifespan, because even in very primitive societies, anybody who survived infancy and then you bring in children, men have no warfare, which is fairly typical of most.
And there does seem to be a very strong genetic component.
My father was 79.
The only reason he died young at 79 is that he drank a lot.
That's true.
You drink yourself to death at 79.
His sister died.
When did my aunt Felipa die?
My aunt Felipa died last year.
She was 100 years old.
for his older sister.
But they were very active physically.
They had to.
They had to be active physically or they would starve to death.
We're not, that's one of our biggest problems.
We're not very active.
I am, but I mean, the most people aren't.
Are you drinking water from there?
Yes.
There we can see Cerrito's grave.
So they would take the young men, they would just draft them, literally draft them into the...
It sounded like in those days in the church, when they put stones on a brick and turned it over.
They were very, definitely very hard done.
I guess I would have done this.
You know, I would say, I always used to, I used to tell my other grandfather, I said, you should just stay there and fight.
They had nothing to fight for.
Yesterday, in Cerritos, a lot of dead stones were seen.
There were revolutionaries who caught a boss, tied him up in a post or in mules.
The Soltán, who left.
All of them were the same, right?
The Caracistes, the Cerarabas, were the same?
All of them were revolving.
At that time, they fought each other.
There were many bandits, many people who stood up with people.
Like Sorrentino, a bandit who stood up.
And others who stood up with others.
Even if they were the same, they would enter the town and say, let's be villagers.
And they would come back and be the same as they were.
There was a problem in Vietnam.
You couldn't tell who the enemy was.
They all looked alike.
They killed cows and gave them to the people and ate them.
Hey, Ella, come here.
This is like one of my older sisters.
How do you do?
Really?
You've been studying?
Excuse me, let me go in.
Oh, were you sitting over here?
Oh, I'm tired.
Let me switch this off.
You know, we have kids who come from Mexico.
And boy, you know that they have it much better off here.
They come out here without nothing.
And in fact, there's two families right here.
I bet you one of them hasn't been here one year.
They've already built their own home, something they've never had before.
And her brother-in-law is... Well, they've been here just about 60 months.
They haven't yet.
But they sure do.
It's going to get much easier here.
What do you think?
It's a more advanced system.
But now there's a lot of opportunity in Mexico, right?
What do you think about the revolution now?
Will it be good or bad for Mexico?
Well, right now I don't know if it will be good or bad.
I feel like I'm permanent.
I'm asking, if there had never been that revolution, in what state would Mexico be right now?
It would be very good.
Better or worse?
Better.
Better than how it is now?
Better than how it is now.
Is it because of the revolution?
In life, which is better in Mexico now, do you think it's because of the revolution or not?
Well, in those times it was because of the revolution and the bad administration of the government.
Yes.
Well, the revolution was necessary.
Well, it would be, it wouldn't be, but the revolution was made out of envy of the presidency.
They used to have revolution after revolution.
They had a hundred in a row.
The word revolution used to be synonymous with the word Mexico.
They all wanted to be president and the only way they could become president was to have a revolution and throw off the other government.
He said the important thing is that she came over here because of that.
No, but not even your mom was happy here.
Not even your mom, right?
And the older families weren't happy here.
They didn't talk about coming back either.
Yes.
Why?
What was it that they were interested in?
Hey ma'am, and when you got here to Rio Grande, where did you sit?
Did you rent a house or what?
Temporary lodging.
Temporary lodging until they got on their feet.
This was set up by the American government during the revolution.
That's why they were in the army post.
Well, Freddy, but they do the same thing now with the people coming from Mexico.
Yes, the Cuban.
All right, take the Cuban.
And they, too, have the dream of going back to Cuba.
That's their dream.
But look, the people that are coming from Mexico, like these people that come, they come here on Saturday, Monday, they're on free lunch, on welfare aid, and see, they get all their benefits.
Now, they don't provide homes now.
In fact, now they're asking them that they must have a home.
Before they can come home.
But why does the U.S. government do that?
It doesn't make any sense.
I think it's humanity wanting to
to help other humans.
I think they look at them as just humans, not as Mexicans.
Well, why do they do it for Cuba?
The Cubans.
This is a good government.
This is a good government that helps its soldiers who come from Spain.
But wouldn't Mexico do the same thing?
I don't think so.
I wouldn't say there's a better retired Mexican.
No, but to help an American who was already expatriated for some reason, looking for a better life, don't you think you would want to help him?
Yes, he admits it all the time.
But to help him with food and coffee.
Not to help the same people.
If you look at the Mexican government when it comes to a politician, for example, a man who goes through politics, through war, they receive him.
The government receives him and gives him protection.
But a bandolero, just to go, because I liked to wear a bandolero, no.
Not anywhere, not here.
No, it's what I said.
But correctly, yes.
Any government of any kind, I know they have given them protection and they give it wherever they want.
The same here as there.
Because here I was once, if a revolutionary came from there for the war, there they were in the house of...
We worked in the bakery and we would bring them food at night.
They would come running from there.
And then the administration came and protected them.
But don't you think, Chema, that if you come back with your family... Don't you think that you could... You have workers.
You're going to have...
I have good people wherever they want to protect me.
No, no.
But it could be a life almost the same as the one here, when you start working with your children.
Yes.
Why not?
I say yes.
I also say yes.
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
But you're saying that...
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
The worker wherever he wants to live, he does well.
The worker wherever he wants
We see the jumps.
But there may be nothing wrong with that way of life.
Well, maybe not, but that's why you get more money.
Most of the Mexican cities now, I would say, there's a very strong sense of what the sonchises are doing.
Well, yes, because they have learned it from here.
Now, we traveled into Mexico last summer.
And we were in Guanajuato, and there was a little boy there, I would say, between five and seven.
That kid was smart, but you could tell that he was among the poorest there.

You know, and I told my children, we had a guide with us, and I told my children, you know, it's a shame that such a bright child may never have the opportunity to become president here in Mexico, while in the United States he might have.
And the guide said, oh, yes, they do.
He said, oh, yes, we have some poor now come up.
They have to get up and go.
And I said, well, I don't think that has been the picture of Mexico.
Because the haves have always been the haves.
And the have-nots are the have-nots.
And a have will not let a have-not go up the ladder.
And he said, well, that picture is changing very rapidly.
And then he told us his own life story.
What was his last story?
Well, that he had been a had-not.
He said, I came down from the mountains, and I had enough intelligence to want to do something for myself.
I left my family back there.
I came over here, this family, this family, evidently with more money.
It took me in when they found out that I had it up here.
He said, and they have given me this life.
And he was, of course, going to college, and he was studying either to be a doctor or something big.
And I said, really?
You know, I asked the question.
I said, really?
He said, oh, yeah, there's a lot of cases like this.
And he showed us.
He said, they come down from those mountains, and there will be people here that will be willing to help.
They don't seem to think so.
Or he didn't seem to think so.
We have slums in this country.
But they don't compare to the slums they have down there.
They are slums, you know, they are slums.
Ooh, like that's the Barrio Independencia from Monterey, which is not so far.
It's worse in Monterey than it is in Guadalupe.
I think it's because Monterey has been attracting such a large number of people who are unskilled from the country side.
And they linger around the edges of Monterey.
There's no way to absorb it.
So you see, yes, I'd say that the value of incandescent in Monterey is probably wonderful, but I've never been.
I'm Ella Montemayor, and I am Mrs. Medina's daughter.
I have been asked what made us get out of being the migrant family that we used to be.
My mother and father had a large family.
He was a migrant worker.
But I have always said that it was this foresight that my mother had
that we had to get out of this way of living.
And so she, they had a high emphasis on education.
And she would stay home with the children, and my dad would go, and she would just try to make live with whatever he sent.
And well, we're not, not any of us are really wealthy.
But we all, at least, we're all stay in school, and our children have an opportunity to stay in school.
I don't know.
And why do you feel your mother had this drive?
I don't know.
I think it was in her.
I mean, some people have it.
That's the only way I can see it.
Some people have it, and some people...
It's an inner drive.
I don't know.
I don't know.
We always tell her that we think that we all inherited from her.
But... Because I see it in school children.
There are some parents that just don't have it.
No matter how much we try to tell them.
They feel that the way they're living is perfect.
And you're now a schoolteacher.
Yes.
In fact, there's at least eight or ten within the family.
I'm a schoolteacher.
My husband's a schoolteacher.
My brother's a schoolteacher.
My sister-in-law's a schoolteacher.
My sister.
I have two, a brother and a sister.
They're schoolteachers in MacAllen.
We've all, well practically all of us, of course now like mother says, her ambition was to have doctors and lawyers.
But when you're climbing up, you just can't skip.
The next thing for us was education.
And so we all got into an education field.
Now I tell my children, now of course they can have
an ambition to become a doctor or a lawyer, because now they have had better opportunities than what I had.
I came from a home where no English was spoken.
So mother could not help us.
And they have had a much better opportunity.
We do a lot of traveling.
They've been exposed to a lot more than what we could have done.
We had to do it practically on our own.
Of course, it was her drive.
I think because, I don't know, and daddy was very
willing to go along with her idea.
How much of the year was he usually gone?
Oh, I would say not more than six months.
Because he didn't know how to write.
And so the communication was very little.
And so he had to come and see his family pretty often.
Or else, you know, a whole year would go by and he really wouldn't know.
So he tried to make it.
I wouldn't say that he'd be gone more than six months.
Three to six months.
And your mother never would go and take you?
Never.
She probably went.
Well, in fact, I think she went until the older ones were ready to start school.
She followed him.
My oldest sister, my grandmother, took her in so she wouldn't miss.
And then as soon as my oldest brother was old enough to go to school, then she stayed.
And from then on, it was a family stay.
Father went.
But we were never, the family was never, now I could say I went one year, but that was because I wanted to go.
I wanted to see what it was like.
And I went my junior year in high school.
That's when I went to try it.
We went during the summer.
What was it like?
Oh, I came back and I thought, mother, never.
This is one thing I'll never do.
I just stay home and go to school.
And I think she emphasized that a lot when we were going to school.
And we came from a family where most of us had perfect attendance because she emphasized it a lot.
If you don't go to school, you're going to end up going with your daddy to the fields.
And we all knew that that was rough out there in the sun.
And some families now do not see it like that.
To them, it's a joy to go, to leave school and go.
I don't know why.
I think it's because we're pushing.
No, and I still tell them, I pass by a field, and I'm like, oh, God, I'm glad we got out of there.
And I tell my kids, that's one of the roughest things to do.
You cannot see how anybody, not even for all the money in the world, doesn't want to go and work on the fields.
And, you know, the living conditions.
I just can't see it.
